# Tailwind and semantic HTML – PandaTrack

## cn() for class names

Use the `cn()` function from `@/lib/styles` to combine and conditionally apply classes (clsx + tailwind-merge).

```tsx
import { cn } from "@/lib/styles";

<div className={cn("base-classes", isActive && "active", className)} />
```

## Repeated Tailwind patterns

- **Global patterns**: Define in `src/app/globals.css` with `@layer components` and `@apply` when used app-wide.
- **Domain/route-specific patterns**: If only used in one area, use scoped CSS or reusable classes in that area’s components.

## Semantic HTML

Use elements that convey meaning: `<button>` for actions, `<nav>` for navigation, `<main>` for main content, `<article>`, `<section>`, `<header>`, `<footer>` as appropriate.

```tsx
// ❌ Avoid
<div onClick={handleSubmit}>Submit</div>
<div><div>Title</div><div>Content...</div></div>

// ✅ Do this
<button type="button" onClick={handleSubmit}>Submit</button>
<article>
  <h1>Title</h1>
  <p>Content...</p>
</article>
```

Choosing the right element improves accessibility and SEO.
